data.content:
**No Thread.Abort migration needed.** Your code uses only `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep` — none of which are affected by the .NET Framework → .NET 8 migration. These APIs work identically in modern .NET. The code will compile and run correctly as-is on `net8.0`.

**Optional modernization** (unrelated to Thread.Abort): You could simplify this with `Parallel.ForEach` or `Task.WhenAll`:

```csharp
public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items)
{
    await Task.WhenAll(items.Select(item => Task.Run(() => Process(item))));
}
```

This is purely a readability/efficiency improvement — not a migration requirement.
